##Book Library API
This is a Book Library API built using Spring Boot. The API allows users to manage books, authors, and categories in a library system.

#Table of Contents
Prerequisites
Setup Instructions
Running the Application
API Endpoints
Testing
Troubleshooting
Prerequisites
Before setting up the project, make sure you have the following installed:

Java 17 or later
Maven 3.8.1 or later
MySQL (or any other database system configured in application.properties)
Postman or cURL for testing API endpoints (optional)
Setup Instructions
1. Clone the Repository
Clone the Book Library API repository to your local machine:

bash
Copy code
git clone https://github.com/yourusername/book-library-api.git
cd book-library-api
2. Database Setup
Create a new database in MySQL (or the database of your choice):

sql
Copy code
CREATE DATABASE booklibrary;
Update the database connection settings in src/main/resources/application.properties:

properties
Copy code
spring.datasource.url=jdbc:mysql://localhost:3306/booklibrary
spring.datasource.username=root
spring.datasource.password=password
spring.jpa.hibernate.ddl-auto=update
3. Dependencies
Make sure you have all the required dependencies:

bash
Copy code
mvn clean install
Running the Application
1. Run the Application Locally
To run the Book Library API locally, use the following Maven command:

bash
Copy code
mvn spring-boot:run
This will start the application on port 8080 by default. You should see the following output when the application is successfully started:

bash
Copy code
Tomcat started on port(s): 8080 (http) with context path ''
2. Access the Application
Once the application is running, you can access the API by visiting:

arduino
Copy code
http://localhost:8080
API Endpoints
Here is a list of available API endpoints for the Book Library API.

1. Books
GET /api/books
Retrieve a list of all books.

bash
Copy code
GET http://localhost:8080/api/books
GET /api/books/{id}
Retrieve a book by its ID.

bash
Copy code
GET http://localhost:8080/api/books/{id}
POST /api/books
Add a new book to the library.

bash
Copy code
POST http://localhost:8080/api/books
Request Body (JSON):

json
Copy code
{
  "title": "The Great Gatsby",
  "author": "F. Scott Fitzgerald",
  "category": "Fiction",
  "isbn": "9780743273565"
}
PUT /api/books/{id}
Update an existing book.

bash
Copy code
PUT http://localhost:8080/api/books/{id}
Request Body (JSON):

json
Copy code
{
  "title": "The Great Gatsby (Updated)",
  "author": "F. Scott Fitzgerald",
  "category": "Classic Fiction",
  "isbn": "9780743273565"
}
DELETE /api/books/{id}
Delete a book by its ID.

bash
Copy code
DELETE http://localhost:8080/api/books/{id}
2. Authors
GET /api/authors
Retrieve a list of all authors.

bash
Copy code
GET http://localhost:8080/api/authors
GET /api/authors/{id}
Retrieve an author by their ID.

bash
Copy code
GET http://localhost:8080/api/authors/{id}
3. Categories
GET /api/categories
Retrieve a list of all categories.

bash
Copy code
GET http://localhost:8080/api/categories
GET /api/categories/{id}
Retrieve a category by its ID.

bash
Copy code
GET http://localhost:8080/api/categories/{id}
Testing
1. Unit Tests
To run unit tests for the project, use the following Maven command:

bash
Copy code
mvn test
The test results will be displayed in the console. You can also check the target/test-classes for detailed test results.

2. Integration Tests
To run integration tests, use the following command:

bash
Copy code
mvn verify
This will execute integration tests and generate test reports in target/failsafe-reports.

Troubleshooting
404 Not Found Error: Ensure the API is running and that you are accessing the correct endpoints. Double-check the URL path.
Database Connection Issues: Ensure your MySQL server is running and that the database credentials in application.properties are correct.
Dependency Issues: Run mvn clean install to ensure all dependencies are downloaded and installed.
Deployment Guide
If you want to deploy the application to a server, follow these steps:

Build the Application:

bash
Copy code
mvn clean install
Create an Executable JAR:

bash
Copy code
mvn package
This will create a book-library-api-1.0-SNAPSHOT.jar file in the target directory.

Deploy the Application:

Copy the JAR file to your server.
Run the application:
bash
Copy code
java -jar book-library-api-1.0-SNAPSHOT.jar
Verify Deployment: Once the application is running on the server, you should be able to access the API via the server’s IP address or domain name.

